Another look at the preceding proof shows that if the set $D$ is a singleton then the set $E$ in \eqref{eq-E} is actually the set of all $\mathcal{A}$-universal points. Thus we have the following.

\begin{corollary}\label{c-gdelta}
Let $T:X\to X$ be a continuous mapping on a separable complete metric space $X$, and let $\mathcal{A}$ be an upper Furstenberg family that has a representation with ${ \text{\rm card}}(D)=1$. Then the set of $\mathcal{A}$-hypercyclic points for $T$ is either empty or a dense $G_\delta$-set.
